.Dd March 31, 2026
.Dt PING 1
.Os Kayoko
.Sh NAME
.Nm ping
.Nd send ICMP ECHO_REQUEST packets to network hosts
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Ar host
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility uses the ICMP protocol's mandatory ECHO_REQUEST datagram to elicit 
an ICMP ECHO_RESPONSE from a host or gateway.
ECHO_REQUEST datagrams (\(dq偶pings\(dq) have an IP and ICMP header, 
followed by a 
.Vt struct timeval
and then an arbitrary number of \(dqpad\(dq bytes used to fill out the packet.
.Pp
When using
.Nm
for fault isolation, it should first be run on the local host, to verify 
that the local network interface is up and running.
Then, hosts and gateways further and further away should be \(dqpinged\(dq.
.Pp
The following statistics are displayed upon termination:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Packets transmitted
The total number of ICMP ECHO_REQUEST packets sent.
.It Packets received
The total number of ICMP ECHO_RESPONSE packets successfully captured.
.It Packet loss
The percentage of packets that failed to return.
.It Round-trip times
The minimum, average, maximum, and standard deviation of the time taken 
for the packets to return, measured in milliseconds with microsecond 
precision.
.El
.Sh IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
The 
.Nm
utility on 
.Os
is implemented in C++ to utilize high-resolution monotonic clock 
interfaces, providing sub-millisecond timing accuracy.
It performs reverse DNS lookups on the provided 
.Ar host
to display canonical names in the output.
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Ping a remote host by IP address:
.Pp
.Dl $ ping 1.1.1.1
.Pp
Ping a host by hostname:
.Pp
.Dl $ ping google.com
.Sh DIAGNOSTICS
The
.Nm
utility exits 0 on success, and >0 if an error occurs. 
Success is defined as receiving at least one response packet.
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr netstat 1 ,
.Xr icmp 4 ,
.Xr ifconfig 8
